SARCOCYSTIS NEURONA IN OPOSSUMS (3)
===================================
[1]
From: NHawekotte@aol.com
Date: Thu, 18 Jan 1996 22:51:49 -0500
Subject: Re: PROMED-AHEAD: Sarcocystis neurona in opossums (2)
Dr. Fenger...
Thank you for your response to my queries about Sarcocystis neurona.
Apologies for miscrediting the research...I did not personally read
the article in Equus; my friend with the horses did and provided the
information. Your info is quite interesting.
I am curious about the differences between the spp. neurona, falcatula
and rileyi. Are all three responsible for the same neurologic symptoms;
are all treatment protocols similar?
Regarding our native marsupial, D. virginiana, I work with them in a
rehabilitation setting. Obviously, given this context, I am not likely
to euthanize them. While they usually carry a load of parasites (as do
other carnivores), they are uniquely resistant to many diseases and
viruses that affect and spread among other animals; I believe they are
vectors for few. In rehab settings, other species present the major
zoonotic concerns. Opossums are also responsible for keeping rodent and
snake populations at bay where there is feed/hay etc in abundance. I
believe there is greater concern with these species...
Opossum feces are soft and last a very short time in natural settings.
Researchers cannot easily locate populations or identify diet as with
other wildife by use of fecal remains. Yet the article in Equus
indicated that sporocytes lasted up to a year, if I understand correctly,
in the feces. What is the setting? What happens to the sporocyte when
the fecal substrate disappears? Do they remain viable in soil?
Merck Veterinary Manual that cats and dogs are likely to be carriers of
the protozoan (although S. neurona is not specifically cited); opossums
are not mentioned as a carrier. Can other carnivores/omnivores --
anything that feeds on cowbirds or starlings -- also provide sanctuary
as secondary host?
Can the sporocytes be detected in fecal floats or smears of the opossum?
Thanks for bearing with this long post, and regards,
Nancy Hawekotte
