[2]
Date: 18 Jan 96 16:32:59 EST
From: "Clara K. Fenger" <74232.1063@compuserve.com>
I want to clarify a few of the items in my previous post to this
group...
Opossums have a relatively small individual range (150-250 acres),
and therefore, trapping and relocating should theoretically be as
effective as killing them. Be sure to release the opossums in areas
that are sufficiently distant from horse-raising property. If you
choose to trap and release them, remember that they can bite, and
are extremely dangerous, similar to most wild animals (although
they rarely carry rabies). Again, be sure to check with state and
local authorities regarding any regulations about handling wildlife.
Alternatively, opossums can be discouraged from entering barns by
covering garbage and feed cans, NOT leaving cat and dog food out at
night, and securing hay lofts and feed rooms as much as possible.
Dogs are excellent opossum deterrents. Personally, I would extremely
fearful of using hay that has opossum excrement on it as feed for
horses.
Preventative measures such as coccidiostats cannot be used in horses
because they are toxic to horses. (They are not that effective in the
prevention of Sarcocystosis anyway) Periodic treatment with pyrimethamine
and sulfonamides has been recommended in the past, but are NOT currently
recommended because this regimen is likely to encourage the development
of resistant protozoa.
-Clara Fenger, DVM, Diplomate ACVIM
"These views are my own, and do not necessarily reflect the views of
the Gluck Equine Research Center."
----------------------------------------------------------------------
[- Nancy Hawekotte makes an excellent point about faecal consistancy.
If not deposited in hay or on feed, as Clara Fenger points out, faeces
will very soon be broken up in pasture by dung beetles and rain, and the
cysts dispersed. Further rain and u/v light will diminish the risk still
further. - MH-J ProMED-Ahead Moderator]
